observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the:

a.	 Municipal Mayor (i) instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct complete inventory of all of its PPE and accomplish the Inventory Report in accordance with Section 124 of Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I. If any unserviceable properties are found it should be counted completely and must be reported in the IIRUP to be approved by the Municipal Mayor pursuant to Section 59 of Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume II. Expendable and Semi-expendable supplies should be identified and segregated from the RPCPPE and must be reported in the RPCI. After the physical inventory-taking, the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant reconcile the result of the physical count of PPE with their respective records and immediately verify and adjust any discrepancies noted; (ii) instruct the designated property officer and other concerned officers to undertake the necessary actions regarding the disposal of its unserviceable PPE in accordance with Section 79 of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and Section 194 of the Rules and Regulations on Supply and Property Management in the Local Governments; and (iii) create Committee on Appraisal of Property that will appraise all the unserviceable properties for subsequent disposal and the appraised value will be reported in the IIRUP;

b.	The Inventory Committee conduct physical count of the road network and prepare RPCLRN for CYs 2016 and below in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-008. After the physical inventory-taking, the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant reconcile the result of the physical count of the road network with their respective records and immediately verify and adjust any discrepancies noted; 

c.Designated GSO (i) prepare Property Card for all PPE and (ii) maintain Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and Local Road Network Property Card for CYs 2016 and below in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-008; and 

d.	Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant and the Designated GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects for CYs 2016 and below.

We recommended that the: 

a.	Municipal Accountant (i) submit the approved request for the time extension in the delivery of goods, otherwise, compute liquidated damages pursuant to Item 3.1, Annex D of Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and demand payment of such from the supplier; (ii) submit the copy of approved compliance of the Municipality to utilize the unexpended balance of ₱92,000.00 generated after the completion of BuB-Local Government Support for DRRM related projects by the DBM for audit purposes; (iii) require the contractor to post/submit irrevocable standby letter of credit/security bond/bank guarantee for the advance payment pursuant to Item 4.2, Annex E of 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;       (iv) submit the Supplemental/Bid Bulletins to support the amendments to the dates of opening of bids; 

b.	Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) (a) adhere with the pertinent provisions of RA No. 9184 on the conduct (i) of procurement transactions by procuring goods based on the relevant characteristics and/or performance requirement instead of basing on brand names and procure only those that are necessary, of equally higher quality but with cheaper price, (ii) pre-bid conference and (iii) examination of the bidding documents; and (b) ensure that the legal, technical and financial documents are appropriate and completely submitted by the bidders; 

c.	Chief of Public Utilities Regulation Officer and Municipal Engineer stop the practice of renting equipment and dump truck pursuant to Item 3.2.b of Appendix I of Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 for projects undertaken By Administration; and

d.	Municipal Accountant, Engineer, and BAC Chairman and Secretariat submit the necessary documents for audit purposes.

observations.reason:
The submitted documents by the SPTD were only a portion of the total necessary documents required. The following documents are still lacking:

Work and Financial Plan (WFP) and sources of Proponent’s Equity Participation in the Project;

Complete project proposals approved/signed by its officers which shall include the objectives, target beneficiaries, feasibility studies, risk assessment, designs, plans, blueprints, charts, etc.;

Sworn affidavit of the secretary of the NGO that none of its incorporators, organizers, directors or officers is an agent of or related by consanguinity or affinity up to the fourth civil degree to the official of the agency authorized to process and/or approve proposed MOA, and release funds;

Approved Summary of Budgetary Requirements detailing the items of expenditure/ disbursement to be incurred in the program/project;

List of priority projects which may be implemented by the NGO published in the newspaper, agency website, bulletin board and the like;

Results of evaluation of financial and technical capability of selected NGO; and

Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) incorporating therein the listed terms and provisions.

observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the:

a. Municipal Mayor and Officials observe strictly the austerity measures set by Department of Interior and Local Government (DILG) and minimize attendance to “Lakbay-Aral”, instead appropriate funds to programs/projects/ activities that will bring immediate socio-economic benefits among its local constituents;

b. Municipal Budget Officer explain the excess charging of the expenses/ disbursement against the appropriated amount for the Employees’ Day and the                Lakbay-Aral for the Barangay Health Worker (BHW), Barangay Nutrition Scholar (BNS) among others; 

c. Municipal Accountant submit the lacking documents to facilitate audit as to legality and propriety of the disbursement, otherwise the transaction would be considered irregular and refund of the full amount shall be made in full immediately; and

d. Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) strictly adhere to the provision of Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (RIRR) of Republic Act (RA) No. 9184 for the procurement of services and explain the deficiencies noted.

We recommended that the:

a.	Municipal officials and employees concerned with CAs for travel immediately liquidate their CAs upon arrival from each travel pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002;

b.	Municipal Accountant and Treasurer (i) submit the necessary documents to support the Report of Disbursements of CA for Emergency Shelter Assistance (ESA); and                          (ii) ensure that all expenses to be paid out of the Petty Cash Fund are         non-recurring, emergency and petty, and amount shall not exceed ₱1,000.00;

c.	Municipal Mayor ensure that the CA to Special Disbursing Officer (SDO)  is for special purpose when it is impractical or difficult to make payments by check; and

d.	Municipal Treasurer                      (i) monitor the fidelity bond of every Accountable Officer (AO) for public funds and request for an increase of bond to cover the maximum cash accountability provided on Bureau of Treasury (BTr) Circular                  No. 02-2009 dated August 6, 2009; and (ii) require the Disbursing Officer (DO) and SDO to maintain cashbook and properly accomplish it pursuant to Section 28 of the MNGAS for LGUs.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor and officials concerned:

a. Establish an Solid Waste Management (SWM) facility that can be used for a long-term period instead of putting up a temporary one and eventually closing it due to non-compliance or other issue and obtain an Environmental Compliance Certificate (ECC) to comply with the requirements Republic Act (RA) No. 9003 and Presidential Decree (PD) No. 1586 for the establishment of SWM facility;

b. Strictly comply with the provisions of RA No. 9003 on the operation of a dumpsite/sanitary landfill instead of the existing open dumpsite to mitigate the harmful effects in the environment of solid wastes generated by the locality and further damage to the health of its constituents;

c. Ensure that the constituents in the remaining 11 barangays illegally dumping their waste elsewhere were informed of proper waste disposal. Moreover, we recommended that the Designated Municipal Environmental and Natural Resources Officer (MENRO) ensure that all policies, programs and activities regarding the SWM of the Municipality were fully enforced; and

d. Call the attention of the junkshop owner in Barangay Villaflor located just along the national highway to properly file the wastes and immediately dispose or recycle them.

We recommended that the:

a. Municipal Mayor and Officials observe strictly the austerity measures set by Department of Interior and Local Government (DILG) and minimize attendance to “Lakbay-Aral”, instead appropriate funds to programs/projects/ activities that will bring immediate socio-economic benefits among its local constituents;

b. Municipal Budget Officer explain the excess charging of the expenses/ disbursement against the appropriated amount for the Employees’ Day and the                Lakbay-Aral for the Barangay Health Worker (BHW), Barangay Nutrition Scholar (BNS) among others; 

c. Municipal Accountant submit the lacking documents to facilitate audit as to legality and propriety of the disbursement, otherwise the transaction would be considered irregular and refund of the full amount shall be made in full immediately; and

d. Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) strictly adhere to the provision of Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (RIRR) of Republic Act (RA) No. 9184 for the procurement of services and explain the deficiencies noted.

We recommended that the:

a. Municipality strictly adhere to the issuance of checks to FA clients in accordance with the provisions set in Section VI B.3.1 of DSWD AO No. 5 series of 2011;

b. Municipal Accountant submit the necessary supporting documents; 

c. Local Chief Executive formulate clear-cut policies and      well-defined guidelines for the granting of all types of donations/FA, which shall provide among others, the following: (i) a clear definition of the qualified beneficiaries and what kind of assistance or donation is chargeable against a specific fund;        (ii) the criteria in determining the amount of donation to be given in every case and the designated person/s that shall be responsible to determine the same; and (iii) complete list of documents to be required for each type of donation/assistance. Moreover, apportionment of funds to more beneficial programs and projects should be carefully considered in order to achieve the desired betterment of the whole constituency; and

d. Municipal Accountant submit the missing vouchers and their complete supporting documents.
